---

<Infographic
  title="Entanglement swapping"
  description="Entanglement swapping joins two Bell pairs into one across a longer distance via a Bell-state measurement at a Bell-state analyser (BSA) node. The endpoints' qubits are entangled afterward despite never having interacted. Chained swaps are the primitive every memory-based quantum repeater is built on. This page covers the protocol, why it works, and how it extends across multiple hops."
  references={[
    "jones-njp-2016",
    "kumar-ijndc-2025",
    "pompili-science-2021",
    "zukowski-prl-1993",
  ]}
>
  <SiteNav slot="nav" currentSubject="swapping" sections={sections} />

  <Center max="var(--wide-width)" gutter="var(--space-3)">
    <Stack space="var(--space-6)">

      <header class="hero" id="overview" data-nav-section>
        <h1>Entanglement swapping</h1>
        <p>
          Two Bell pairs sharing one node can be <strong>swapped</strong> into a single Bell pair
          spanning the two outer endpoints — without those endpoints ever interacting and
          without measuring the qubits being networked. The trick is a Bell-state
          measurement at the shared node: the BSM consumes the two qubits at the BSA,
          and what's left is a Bell pair between the two distant qubits, up to a
          Pauli correction that's announced via a classical
          channel <SourceNote id="zukowski-prl-1993" />.
        </p>
        <p>
          Swapping is the primitive that <strong>extends the reach</strong> of a quantum
          network. A direct Bell pair between Alice and Bob in standard fibre runs out
          of usable rate after a few tens of kilometres. At 0.20 dB/km, photon survival
          halves every 15 km — so only ~1 % make it through 100 km. Current heralded
          entanglement demonstrations sit in the 10–50 km range over deployed
          fibre <SourceNote id="knaut-nature-2024" />. Chains of swaps stitch shorter
          pairs together so the end-to-end pair can span much further. Every memory-based
          quantum repeater — and every link architecture in
          <a href={url("/distribution")}>distribution</a> — is built on this
          primitive <SourceNote id="kumar-ijndc-2025" />.
        </p>
      </header>

      <section id="protocol" data-nav-section>
        <h2>The setup and protocol</h2>
        <p>
          Three parties: Alice, a Bell-state analyser (BSA), and Bob. Two Bell pairs already exist:
          <strong>A</strong> at Alice paired with <strong>A′</strong> at R, and
          <strong>B′</strong> at the BSA paired with <strong>B</strong> at Bob. The BSA
          holds <strong>A′</strong> and <strong>B′</strong>, one qubit from each
          pre-shared pair; the qubits at Alice and Bob are never touched until the
          final Pauli correction.
        </p>
        <p>
          Three steps follow, structurally identical to teleportation — except that
          what's being "teleported" is Alice's half of the first pair onto Bob's
          qubit, with the BSA performing the BSM in the middle.
        </p>

        <ol class="sw-steps">
          <li>
            <strong>BSM at the BSA.</strong> The BSA performs a Bell-state measurement
            on its two qubits <Math tex="R_1" /> and <Math tex="R_2" />. Both pre-shared
            pairs (<Math tex="A \\leftrightarrow R_1" /> and
            <Math tex="R_2 \\leftrightarrow B" />) are consumed by the measurement. The
            outcome is two classical bits identifying which of the four Bell states the
            BSM landed on, which in turn determines which Bell state
            <Math tex="A" /> and <Math tex="B" /> are now in.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Classical communication.</strong> The BSA sends the 2 bits to Bob
            (or Alice — either endpoint will do).
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Pauli correction.</strong> Bob applies one of <Math tex="I" />,
            <Math tex="X" />, <Math tex="Z" />, <Math tex="ZX" /> to his qubit
            <Math tex="B" /> based on the bits. After the correction,
            <Math tex="A" /> and <Math tex="B" /> are in the Bell state
            <Math tex="|\\Phi^+\\rangle_{AB}" /> — a freshly minted Bell pair across the
            full distance.
          </li>
        </ol>

        <figure class="sw" id="sw-fig" data-sw>
          <svg viewBox="0 0 800 260" role="img"
               aria-label="Entanglement-swapping animation. Top row: two short Bell pairs A↔A′ and B′↔B. The BSA performs a BSM on A′ and B′; two classical bits travel to Bob; Bob applies a Pauli correction. Bottom row: the resulting long Bell pair A↔B."
               data-sw-svg>
            <defs>
              <radialGradient id="sw-cloud-teal" cx="0.5" cy="0.5" r="0.5">
                <stop offset="0%"   stop-color="var(--tp-teal, #4cc8c0)" stop-opacity="0.95"/>
                <stop offset="40%"  stop-color="var(--tp-teal, #4cc8c0)" stop-opacity="0.55"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="var(--tp-teal, #4cc8c0)" stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
              <radialGradient id="sw-cloud-spent" cx="0.5" cy="0.5" r="0.5">
                <stop offset="0%"   stop-color="#7a8390" stop-opacity="0.9"/>
                <stop offset="40%"  stop-color="#7a8390" stop-opacity="0.45"/>
                <stop offset="100%" stop-color="#7a8390" stop-opacity="0"/>
              </radialGradient>
              <marker id="sw-arr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5"
                      markerWidth="6" markerHeight="6" orient="auto">
                <path d="M0,0 L10,5 L0,10 Z" fill="var(--color-text-soft)"/>
              </marker>
            </defs>

            {/* Endpoint labels */}
            <text x="50"  y="20" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-label">Alice</text>
            <text x="400" y="20" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-label">BSA</text>
            <text x="750" y="20" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-label">Bob</text>

            {/* Dashed relay box around A′ and B′ — same physical location. */}
            <rect data-sw-relay-box x="325" y="32" width="150" height="56" rx="4"
                  fill="none" stroke="var(--color-rule)" stroke-width="1"
                  stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.55"/>

            {/* ---- Top row: Alice (A), relay (A′, B′), Bob (B) ---- */}
            <circle cx="50"  cy="60" r="18" fill="var(--color-bg)"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="50"  y="65" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-node-lbl">A</text>
            <circle cx="750" cy="60" r="18" fill="var(--color-bg)"
                    stroke="var(--color-text)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="750" y="65" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-node-lbl">B</text>

            {/* A′ and B′ photonic clouds — the relay's two qubits that
                get consumed by the BSM. */}
            <g data-sw-aprime transform="translate(359 60)">
              <circle data-sw-aprime-cloud r="18" fill="url(#sw-cloud-teal)"/>
              <text y="5" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-node-lbl">A′</text>
            </g>
            <g data-sw-bprime transform="translate(441 60)">
              <circle data-sw-bprime-cloud r="18" fill="url(#sw-cloud-teal)"/>
              <text y="5" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-node-lbl">B′</text>
            </g>

            {/* Bell-pair wavy lines (A↔A′ and B′↔B). Magenta, same
                wavelength/amp as the bottom result line. */}
            <path data-sw-pair-aa class="sw-ent"
                  d="M 68,60 q 17,-9 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0"/>
            <path data-sw-pair-bb class="sw-ent"
                  d="M 459,60 q 17,-9 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0 t 34,0"/>

            {/* ---- BSM apparatus (same geometry as images/BSM.svg).
                Greyed out until the BSM phase fires. ---- */}
            <svg data-sw-bsm x="300" y="62" width="200" height="169"
                 viewBox="0 0 640 540" overflow="visible"
                 color="var(--color-text)" opacity="0.22">
              <defs>
                <symbol id="sw-bsm-detector" overflow="visible">
                  <path d="M -14,0 A 14,14 0 0 1 14,0 Z" fill="currentColor"/>
                </symbol>
              </defs>
              <line x1="190" y1="50"  x2="450" y2="310" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="310" x2="510" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="310" x2="390" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="50"  x2="190" y2="310" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="190" y1="310" x2="130" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <line x1="190" y1="310" x2="250" y2="370" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" fill="none" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-dasharray="14,10"/>
              <rect x="312" y="140" width="16" height="80" rx="4" fill="currentColor"/>
              <polygon points="190,270 230,310 190,350 150,310" fill="#d9eef9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              <line x1="190" y1="270" x2="190" y2="350" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <polygon points="450,270 490,310 450,350 410,310" fill="#d9eef9" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="4" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              <line x1="450" y1="270" x2="450" y2="350" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
              <use href="#sw-bsm-detector" transform="translate(130,370) rotate(-135)"/>
              <use href="#sw-bsm-detector" transform="translate(250,370) rotate(135)"/>
              <use href="#sw-bsm-detector" transform="translate(390,370) rotate(-135)"/>
              <use href="#sw-bsm-detector" transform="translate(510,370) rotate(135)"/>
            </svg>

            {/* ---- Classical channel (dashed line + bit pair).
                 The (0, 1) pulse sits ON the line; the "2 classical bits"
                 label sits BELOW the line so it doesn't clash with the pulse. ---- */}
            <line x1="455" y1="240" x2="720" y2="240"
                  stroke="var(--color-text-soft)" stroke-width="1"
                  stroke-dasharray="4,3" opacity="0.6"
                  marker-end="url(#sw-arr)"/>
            <text x="590" y="268" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-channel">2 classical bits</text>

            <g data-sw-bits opacity="0">
              <text data-sw-bits-text x="475" y="244" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-bit">(0, 1)</text>
            </g>

            {/* Pauli badge that lands on B during the correction phase. */}
            <g data-sw-lock opacity="0" transform="translate(750 100)">
              <rect x="-20" y="-14" width="40" height="28" rx="4"
                    fill="var(--color-bg)" stroke="var(--tp-purple, #a866c8)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
              <text data-sw-lock-letter x="0" y="6" text-anchor="middle" class="sw-pauli-badge">X</text>
            </g>

            {/* ---- Final A↔B Bell pair, traced in on the SAME ROW as
                A and B. After phase 2 the A′/B′ clouds have faded and
                the relay-R box dissolves (data-sw-relay-box), so the
                long wavy line spans the row cleanly. ---- */}
            <path data-sw-pair-ab class="sw-ent" pathLength="1"
                  stroke-dasharray="1 1" stroke-dashoffset="1" opacity="0"
                  d="M 68,60 q 17.5,-10 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0 t 35,0"/>

          </svg>

          <ol class="sw-step-list" data-sw-steps>
            <li data-sw-step="1"><strong>1.</strong> Two pre-shared Bell pairs: A↔A′ at Alice and B′↔B at Bob, meeting at the BSA</li>
            <li data-sw-step="2"><strong>2.</strong> R performs a Bell-state measurement on A′ and B′</li>
            <li data-sw-step="3"><strong>3.</strong> The 2-bit BSM outcome travels to Bob over a classical channel</li>
            <li data-sw-step="4"><strong>4.</strong> Bob applies the matching Pauli correction (<em>I</em>, <em>X</em>, <em>Z</em>, or <em>XZ</em>)</li>
            <li data-sw-step="5"><strong>5.</strong> A and B share a fresh Bell pair — they never interacted</li>
          </ol>

          <figcaption>
            Top row: two short Bell pairs (magenta wavy lines) sit on either side of
            the BSA. Its BSM consumes <strong>A′</strong> and
            <strong>B′</strong> — their clouds turn grey the moment they enter the
            apparatus. Two classical bits emerge on the channel and travel to Bob,
            who reads them and applies the matching Pauli. Bottom row: the resulting
            long <strong>A</strong>↔<strong>B</strong> Bell pair traces in as the
            correction lands. The cycle iterates through the four Bell outcomes.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section id="chains" data-nav-section>
        <h2>Chained swapping for reach</h2>
        <p>
          One swap doubles the reach of an unaided link. A chain of <Math tex="n" />
          swaps links <Math tex="n+1" /> short pairs into a single Bell pair spanning the
          full distance. Each BSA in the chain performs its own BSM and broadcasts its
          2-bit result; the corrections compose at one of the endpoints. Memory-based
          repeaters use this pattern as their core operation, with quantum memories at
          each node holding the qubits while pairs are generated and swaps are
          coordinated <SourceNote id="jones-njp-2016" />.
        </p>

        <h3 id="canonical-1g">The canonical 1G repeater</h3>
        <p>
          The four primitives so far — heralded entanglement generation (EG), Bell-state
          measurement, swapping, and quantum memory — compose into one workflow. This is
          the <strong>first-generation</strong> repeater design proposed by Briegel, Dür,
          Cirac and Zoller <SourceNote id="bdcz-prl-1998" /> and surveyed
          in <SourceNote id="sangouard-rmp-83" />, <SourceNote id="azuma-rmp-95" />. The
          diagram below traces a 4-hop chain from <strong>Alice</strong> through three
          quantum repeaters (R₁, R₂, R₃) to <strong>Bob</strong> from start to
          finish: <strong>green</strong> dots are live matter qubits in memory,
          <strong>blue</strong> dots are flying photons used only inside the EG round,
          <strong>grey</strong> dots are matter qubits already spent by a Bell measurement,
          and <strong>blue</strong> wavy lines are entanglement.
        </p>

        <figure class="onegen" data-1g>
          <div class="onegen-controls" data-1g-controls>
            <span class="onegen-phase" data-1g-phase>EG</span>
            <div class="onegen-playback" role="group" aria-label="Animation playback controls">
              {/* Inline SVG icons — monochrome on every platform. The
                  Unicode playback glyphs render as emoji on phones
                  regardless of the U+FE0E text-variation selector. */}
              <button class="onegen-btn" type="button" data-1g-ctl="back" aria-label="Step back" title="Step back">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M6 5v14h2V5zM20 5L9 12l11 7z" fill="currentColor"/></svg>
              </button>
              <button class="onegen-btn" type="button" data-1g-ctl="play" aria-label="Pause" title="Play / pause">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M7 5h3v14H7zM14 5h3v14h-3z" fill="currentColor"/></svg>
              </button>
              <button class="onegen-btn" type="button" data-1g-ctl="fwd" aria-label="Step forward" title="Step forward">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M16 5v14h2V5zM4 5v14l11-7z" fill="currentColor"/></svg>
              </button>
              <button class="onegen-btn" type="button" data-1g-ctl="loop" aria-label="Loop this phase" title="Loop this phase only" aria-pressed="false">
                <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18" aria-hidden="true"><path d="M17.65 6.35A8 8 0 1 0 19.5 14.5h-2.05a6 6 0 1 1-1.41-6.95L13 11h7V4z" fill="currentColor"/></svg>
              </button>
              <button class="onegen-btn onegen-btn--speed" type="button" data-1g-ctl="speed" aria-label="Playback speed" title="Playback speed">1×</button>
            </div>
            <button class="onegen-btn" type="button" data-1g-download aria-label="Download this animation as SVG snapshot" title="Download SVG">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M12 3v12m0 0l-4-4m4 4l4-4M5 21h14" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <button class="onegen-btn" type="button" data-1g-fullscreen aria-label="View this animation full-screen" title="Full screen">
              <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width="18" height="18" aria-hidden="true">
                <path d="M4 10V4h6M20 10V4h-6M4 14v6h6M20 14v6h-6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
          </div>
          <svg viewBox="0 -30 1100 600" role="img"
               aria-label="Canonical 1G repeater across A — R₁ — R₂ — R₃ — B. EG: each adjacent pair emits matter–photon Bell pairs whose photons meet at a midpoint photonic Bell-state analyser; a successful herald collapses the two distant matter qubits into a Bell pair. 1st ES: parallel local Bell measurements at R₁ and R₃ extend the entanglement to A↔R₂ and R₂↔B. 2nd ES: a final Bell measurement at R₂ delivers one long A↔B Bell pair. Each row is a 'repeat until success' loop."
               data-1g-svg>
            <defs>
